{"id": "31b01293a84d4f05ba3c3bde46a71ed6", "timestamp": "2025-12-11 08:11:38", "name": "Scientist0", "content": "This is a timely and impactful direction to pursue, especially given the growing reliance on AI-generated code in both research and production environments. While many current evaluation frameworks for code generation—such as CodeBLEU, PASS@k, and ExactMatch—emphasize precision (i.e., how many generated solutions are correct), they often under-penalize missed correct solutions, which directly affects recall.\n\nMy proposal centers on designing a scoring mechanism that prioritizes *functional correctness* by **emphasizing recall over precision**. The core idea is to ensure that evaluation metrics do not reward models merely for producing syntactically plausible or partially correct code, but instead incentivize them to explore a broader space of valid solutions, thereby reducing false negatives.\n\nOne key insight comes from testing practices in software engineering: a function can be implemented correctly in multiple ways (e.g., iterative vs. recursive, different algorithmic approaches). Current metrics often treat all deviations from a reference solution as errors—even when functionally equivalent—leading to artificially low recall estimates.\n\nTo address this, I propose a **recall-oriented evaluation framework** built on three pillars:\n\n1. **Behavioral Equivalence Testing**: Instead of relying solely on string or AST matching, we use test case coverage—including edge cases, property-based tests, and differential testing—to determine whether a generated program behaves correctly across a wide input spectrum. A model that generates diverse correct implementations should score higher than one that consistently produces the same correct solution (high precision, low recall).\n\n2. **Solution Space Modeling**: We can construct a probabilistic model of the space of correct solutions for a given programming problem—using symbolic execution, program synthesis, or clustering of known correct variants. The scoring mechanism would then measure how much of this space the model covers, rewarding breadth of functional correctness.\n\n3. **Recall-Weighted Scoring Function**: Define a new metric, say **Recall@Correct**, which computes the proportion of reachable correct solutions that the model successfully generates within a fixed budget (e.g., top-k samples). This could be normalized by problem difficulty and augmented with confidence calibration to avoid rewarding random exploration.\n\nAn innovative extension would be to integrate *failure analysis* into the scoring: if a model repeatedly fails on a particular class of correct solutions (e.g., dynamic programming variants), the score would reflect systemic gaps in functional understanding, not just output accuracy.\n\nThis approach shifts the paradigm from \"how often is the model right?\" to \"how comprehensively does the model capture correctness?\", which is crucial for safety-critical or educational applications where missing valid solutions can have real consequences.\n\nI believe this aligns well with our team’s strengths in ML evaluation, program analysis, and interpretable AI. Moreover, it opens avenues for new datasets (e.g., multi-solution coding benchmarks) and model training strategies (e.g., diversity-aware fine-tuning). Would love to hear thoughts on feasibility, potential pitfalls, or connections to related work others might see.", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[95mScientist0\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "8251727225224029babe2b2676995c86", "timestamp": "2025-12-11 08:11:43", "name": "Scientist0", "content": "The proposal introduces a recall-oriented evaluation framework for AI-generated code, prioritizing *functional correctness* and **breadth of solution coverage** over precision. Key elements include:  \n\n- **Behavioral Equivalence Testing**: Using comprehensive test suites (edge cases, property-based testing) to assess functional correctness beyond syntactic similarity.  \n- **Solution Space Modeling**: Mapping the space of valid solutions via symbolic execution or clustering to evaluate how many correct variants a model generates.  \n- **Recall@Correct Metric**: A new scoring function measuring the proportion of correct solutions a model produces within a top-k sample limit, rewarding recall and diversity.  \n\nThe framework also incorporates **failure analysis** to identify systematic model gaps (e.g., missing dynamic programming solutions), enhancing diagnostic value. This shift—from accuracy alone to *comprehensive correctness*—supports safer, more robust code generation in critical applications and enables new benchmarks and training approaches focused on solution diversity.", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[95mScientist0\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "6870e2067a954529854d4d5059e6360c", "timestamp": "2025-12-11 08:11:43", "name": "Scientist0", "content": "[retrieved]:", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[95mScientist0\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "537f2032438f49199dbfca4685934dde", "timestamp": "2025-12-11 08:12:10", "name": "Scientist0", "content": "Building on the compelling direction laid out in the previous turn—particularly the emphasis on *functional correctness* through a recall-oriented lens—I’d like to deepen the discussion by refining our conceptual framework and addressing practical challenges in operationalizing such a metric.\n\nOne critical insight from the prior proposal is that **precision-focused metrics (like exact match or BLEU) penalize semantically correct but syntactically diverse code**, which inherently limits our ability to capture the true capability of modern code generation models. These models often sample from a broad distribution of valid programs, especially when prompted with \"think step-by-step\" or asked to generate multiple solutions. Yet current evaluation paradigms discard all but one “golden” reference, leading to an underestimation of model performance.\n\nTo prioritize **recall over precision**, we must shift from asking *\"Is this output exactly what we expected?\"* to *\"Does this output live within the space of correct behaviors?\"* This requires two foundational components:\n\n---\n\n### 1. **Defining the Solution Space via Behavioral Equivalence**\nWe need a robust method for characterizing the set of functionally equivalent programs. One promising path is leveraging **symbolic execution** and **program equivalence checking** tools (e.g., SMT solvers, KLEE, or recent neural-symbolic verifiers) to group generated outputs into behavioral equivalence classes. For example, different implementations of quicksort (in-place vs. functional style), or iterative vs. recursive Fibonacci, should be clustered as one correct class.\n\nAdditionally, **property-based testing** (à la QuickCheck) can serve as a scalable proxy: if a generated function satisfies key logical properties (e.g., associativity, base case handling, input-output consistency) across thousands of generated inputs, it can be considered part of the correct solution manifold—even if structurally novel.\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Designing Recall@Correct(k): A New Evaluation Primitive**\nLet’s formalize the proposed scoring mechanism:\n> **Recall@Correct(k)** = (Number of *distinct correct solution variants* generated within top-k samples) / (Total number of known feasible correct solution patterns in the equivalence space)\n\nThis differs fundamentally from pass@k, which only measures whether *any* correct solution exists among k attempts. Instead, Recall@Correct rewards **diversity within correctness**—a model that generates five different working sorting algorithms should score higher than one that repeatedly yields slight permutations of the same merge sort implementation.\n\nBut here's a crucial nuance: **how do we bound the denominator?** We can’t assume perfect knowledge of all possible correct programs. So we propose using **clustering over symbolic representations** (e.g., program graphs, control flow signatures) combined with test-suite validation to approximate the total solution space per task. Over time, this becomes a living benchmark—expanded via community contributions or automated solution discovery.\n\n---\n\n### Addressing the Precision Trade-off\nA natural concern arises: doesn't emphasizing recall risk encouraging verbose, redundant, or inefficient code? Yes—but that’s where **multi-axis evaluation** comes in. We envision Recall@Correct not as a replacement, but as the **primary axis** in a new evaluation matrix, supplemented by secondary filters:\n- **Efficiency penalties** (time/space complexity estimation)\n- **Readability scores** (learned or rule-based)\n- **Security linters** (to filter dangerous patterns even if functionally correct)\n\nThese act as soft constraints, ensuring high-recall outputs remain practically useful.\n\n---\n\n### Impact & Innovation\nBy anchoring evaluation in **functional diversity**, this approach enables several transformative applications:\n- **Training objectives** that encourage exploration of alternative correct strategies (via reinforcement learning with intrinsic motivation).\n- **Safer deployment** in mission-critical systems: a model with high Recall@Correct is less likely to miss entire classes of algorithmic solutions.\n- **New benchmarks** like *DiverseCodeBench*, where tasks are scored based on coverage of known solution families (e.g., dynamic programming, greedy, backtracking).\n\nMoreover, analyzing *which* correct solutions a model fails to generate reveals deeper architectural biases—e.g., Transformers favoring left-to-right constructions may under-represent tail-recursive forms.\n\n---\n\nIn summary, I advocate for advancing this research by building both the **theoretical foundation** (defining behavioral equivalence under uncertainty) and the **empirical toolkit** (automated clustering + testing pipelines) needed to make Recall@Correct a reliable, interpretable standard. This isn’t just about better metrics—it’s about reshaping how we define *competence* in AI-generated code.", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[95mScientist0\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "eb455f74a4c847699bbcd4a0039ae162", "timestamp": "2025-12-11 08:12:18", "name": "Scientist0", "content": "Building on the prior proposal, Scientist0 refines the recall-oriented evaluation framework by emphasizing **behavioral equivalence** as a foundation for assessing functional correctness and advocating for the formalization of **Recall@Correct(k)** as a core metric. Key advancements include:\n\n- **Defining solution spaces** using symbolic execution and property-based testing to group semantically equivalent but syntactically diverse programs (e.g., different sorting implementations) into equivalence classes.\n- **Formalizing Recall@Correct(k)** to measure not just correctness but *diversity* among correct outputs—rewarding models that generate distinct valid solutions rather than redundant variants.\n- Addressing the challenge of estimating the **total feasible solution space** via clustering of program representations (e.g., control flow graphs) and iterative benchmark expansion through community or automated discovery.\n- Proposing a **multi-axis evaluation model**, where Recall@Correct serves as the primary metric, complemented by secondary filters for efficiency, readability, and security to mitigate risks of low-quality yet correct code.\n- Highlighting broader impacts: enabling diversity-aware training objectives, safer AI deployment through comprehensive solution coverage, and new benchmarks like *DiverseCodeBench*.\n- Identifying next steps: developing theoretical foundations for behavioral equivalence under uncertainty and building practical tooling for automated clustering and testing.\n\nThis evolution shifts the definition of code generation competence from \"producing the expected output\" to \"exploring the full space of correct behaviors.\"", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[95mScientist0\u001b[0m"}
